column10: TXTmaterialType. In the course of the research that culminated in the paper, which of the following types of research materials were produced? (Check all that apply, regardless of whether they are open to public or not.)
column11: TYPstudy[stumat]. Study materials [Materials produced by researchers and presented to participants to elicit their responses	Includes: Questionnaire	Includes: Experiment instructions, tutorials and training/practice trials	Includes: Instruction texts, researcher scripts, and interviewer’s scripts that only researchers see	Includes: Both stimuli that are manually produced or generated by a piece of software	Includes: Experimental software and parameters needed to “generate” or “present” stimuli  (For example, if you test the guessability of password and write a script to generate passwords that will be shown to participants. The script is considered to be in this category.)	Includes: Technology probes and cultural probes that are custom-made by the authors	Example: In a Fitts’s law study of movement time and index of difficulties, the following materials are in this category: (1) the software that presents targets and capture the cursor movements and (2) the list of height and width of the targets.	Excludes: Off-the shelf software (e.g., Google Form for a survey)	Excludes: Any results or data collected (see below)]
column12: TYPresQL[QLraw]. Results or their derivatives that are frequently generated from qualitative studies [Raw qualitative data before coding	Examples: photos, video, or audio recordings and responses written by participants	Includes: the transcript of the video or audio recordings]
column13: TYPresQL[QLcoded]. Results or their derivatives that are frequently generated from qualitative studies [Coded qualitative data	“Coding” is a process of assigning labels to a chunk of content	Example: labels or categories that are used to represent a chunk of text transcribed from an interview	Includes: annotations made directly on the video or audio timeline]
column14: TYPresQL[QLcBook]. Results or their derivatives that are frequently generated from qualitative studies [Coding manual for researchers to annotate raw data	A procedure for interpreting and coding raw data, and optionally, a brief description or example quotes for each code. Such list is shared within a team of researchers to ensure that everybody shares the same procedure to associate labels with each chunk of content.]
column15: TYPresQT[QTraw]. Results or their derivatives that are generated from quantitative studies [Raw quantitative data before preprocessing	Example: responses or response times for each trial (e.g., for forced with options A, B, & C, the chosen option is the response)	Example: log files or raw responses	Example: demographic information gathered from questionnaires	Example: in a Fitts’s law study, record the exact coordinates of the click rather than the offset coordinates	Excludes: amount of error or correctness and error rate (see the next option)]
column16: TYPresQT[QTprp]. Results or their derivatives that are generated from quantitative studies [Quantitative data that has been processed, summarized, or otherwise derived from raw data in any way	Includes: amount of error or correctness and error rate (e.g., in Fitts’s law study the distance of the click from the center of the target)	Includes: quantitative data derived from qualitative results (e.g., frequency of code occurrences in the interview transcripts)	Example: an input table for ANOVA.]
column17: TYPresQT[QTsrc]. Results or their derivatives that are generated from quantitative studies [Source code for data analysis	Includes: any source code involved in transforming the raw data to the final results	Includes: any form of source code (textual, graphical, mixed)	Examples: code for data preprocessing, statistical tests, or plotting charts.	Excludes: Other types of software that aren not used to analyze data]
column18: TYPprod[SW]. Product or prototype [Software	Includes: Source code for a novel artifact or tool that is the focus of the paper	Includes: Software created from non-textual programming such as Max/MSP or Interface builder	Includes: Software developed in past publications that are used in the paper (e.g., published software at UIST and published a long-term study at CHI.)	Excludes: Commercially-available software	Excludes: Data analysis code (see above)	Excludes: Study stimuli or source code of software that presents stimuli to participants (see above)]
column19: TYPprod[HW]. Product or prototype [Hardware	Includes: Source files for creating hardware, which is either the focus of the paper or a tool for an empirical study.	Examples: Schematics, PCBs, 3D models	Excludes: Commercial off-the-shelf hardware that is used without modifications.]
